**Abstract:** Essay titled "Did Sartre Ever Cease Being an Existentialist?" examining Sartre's relationship to Marxism and existentialism throughout his career. Argues that despite Sartre's claim in Search for a Method that existentialism was an "enclave of Marxism," he later admitted this was a mistake and ultimately remained an existentialist because Marx's philosophy cannot accommodate genuine human freedom. Provides detailed analysis of the incompatibility between Marxist determinism and Sartre's conception of human agency.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Important scholarly essay demonstrating Monasterio's mature understanding of Sartre's philosophical development and his critique of Marxist determinism; relevant to understanding freedom and human agency.

